# Composer

Do **not** run `composer` on the host. Use the PHP container with your UID so `vendor/` stays owned by you:

```bash
docker compose exec -T -u "$(id -u):$(id -g)" php composer update
docker compose exec -T -u "$(id -u):$(id -g)" php composer require vendor/package
docker compose exec -T -u "$(id -u):$(id -g)" php composer install
```

Commit updated `composer.lock` after dependency changes. Production installs via `deploy/remote-setup.sh` in the same container.
